"Overall, we were happy to see an addition to the 312 series here. They take it, obviously, away from the pale wheatiness of the original, giving more hops and pale ambers and toast for an IPA or pale ale lover to bite into. The malts, however, seem rushed, allowing for much more infiltration of the hops, and of curious inherent tropical fruitiness to take hold, erasing the strict balance from the grain bill. We are certainly being strict in our dissection, but figured that the lack of balance was the most notable detriment to this guy. The flavor tends to just peter out, without much to bolster or keep your interest. We hope this is not representative of what is to come from the new Goose Island."
