"I am really digging that my beer was born on my 49th birthday and so I am going with an aggro pour to celebrate. I netted two fingers of rocky, tawny head with persistent retention as the result. Beautiful lacing began to appear as it fell, so I leaned in for a sniff. The pine and grapefruit-citrus nose was as prevalent as any AIPA and my mouth was watering in anticipation. Color was a gorgeous deep-gold (SRM = > 5, < 7) with NE-quality clarity. It should come as no surprise that the Unholy Trio of Midas, Mammon and Croesus suddenly appeared to beg for a sip, but I was having none of it. Mouthfeel was medium-to-full and the hops were much more prevalent than the label had led me to expect. APA?!? If they say so, but this was really drinking like an AIPA, which was okay by me, actually. Maybe it speaks to how we urban dwellers roll. We need more hops than they can handle in those little soft cities. Finish was dry and I suppose that it could have been as dry and puckering as alum, were it not for their purported malt backbone. All I ask is that they consider putting this beer in a CAN."
